IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: Creighton University, founded in 1878, is one of 28 Jesuit, Catholic universities in the U.S. Through its 9 colleges and schools, Creighton provides over 4,200 undergraduate and nearly 4,000 professional and graduate students an atmosphere that challenges them academically and professionally, and supports and inspires them individually. Community service is a hallmark of Creighton's Jesuit, Catholic tradition and foundational to its mission.
IRS990.MissionDesc: Creighton University is a Catholic and Jesuit comprehensive university committed to excellence in its selected undergraduate, graduate and professional programs. As Catholic, Creighton is dedicated to the pursuit of truth in all its forms and is guided by the living tradition of the Catholic Church. As Jesuit, Creighton participates in the tradition of the Society of Jesus which provides an integrating vision of the world that arises out of the knowledge and love of Jesus Christ. As comprehensive, Creighton's education embraces several colleges and professional schools and is directed to the intellectual, social, spiritual, physical and recreational aspects of students' lives and to the promotion of justice. Creighton exists for students and learning. Members of the Creighton community are challenged to reflect on transcendent values, including their relationship with God, in an atmosphere of freedom of inquiry, belief and religious worship.
IRS990.Desc: Higher Education: Instruction - Creighton University, founded in 1878, is a private, Catholic, Jesuit educational institution with primary campuses in Omaha, NE and Phoenix, AZ with nearly 8,200 students of diverse faiths, races, and ethnic backgrounds from across the United States and 56 countries. The University provides its over 4,200 undergraduate and nearly 4,000 professional and graduate students a balanced educational experience, a rigorous academic agenda and a broad range of disciplines. Creighton's distinctive approach to education instills not just information but ideals, imbues not just technical skills but critical and creative thinking, and inspires not just competence but professional distinction and faith-based leadership and service. In addition to the College of Arts and Sciences, the University's oldest and largest school or college, Creighton University includes the Heider College of Business, the College of Nursing, the Graduate School, the Schools of Dentistry, Law, Medicine, Pharmacy and Health Professions, and College of Professional and Continuing Education.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: Student Life Programs (including Auxiliary Services) - Guided by Jesuit, Catholic values and in support of Creighton University's mission, the Division of Student Life fosters holistic student development in the Ignatian tradition through its programs and services, to produce students engaged in their communities with compassion, confidence, and character. Student Life programs include Student Counseling Services; Student Health Education and Compliance; Community Standards and Student Conduct; New Student Orientation and Transition Programs; Student Leadership and Involvement Center - includes oversight of Creighton Students Union (student government), Fraternity and Sorority Life, and over 350 registered student organizations; Recreation and Wellness - includes intramural/club sports and fitness programs; Housing & Residential Life (approximately 2,200 students live in one of the eight residence halls on campus); Dining Services; Student Centers; Conference & Event Services; Business Operations; and Creighton University's Retreat Center in Griswold, IA. Student Life services are provided on both the Omaha, NE campus as well as the Phoenix, AZ Health Sciences campus.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: Higher Education: Health Care Services - Creighton University's health sciences schools currently provide healthcare education for nearly 3,600 dental, medical, physician assistant, nursing, pharmacy, and occupational and physical therapy students. Health sciences students are required to complete clinical training hours as part of their education. Clinical training is arranged through partnerships with healthcare providers and via university owned and operated clinical sites for dental, pharmacy, and occupational and physical therapy.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Schedule D, Part X, Line 2 FIN 48 (ASC 740) footnote
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The University has been recognized by the Internal Revenue Service as a tax exempt organization under Section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code. U.S. GAAP requires management to evaluate tax positions taken and recognize a tax liability (or asset) if the organization has taken an uncertain position that more likely than not would not be sustained upon examination by the Internal Revenue Service. The University is subject to routine audits by taxing jurisdictions; however, there are currently no audits in progress for any tax periods. After evaluating the tax positions for the University, none are considered to be uncertain. As of June 30, 2024, and 2023, the University had no liability for unrecognized tax benefits.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Schedule E, Part I, Line 3 RACIALLY NONDISCRIMINATORY POLICY
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Creighton University's nondiscrimination policy is stated in all publications from Admissions and in all brochures issued by the Registrar. There is also a link to the policy at the bottom of the University's internet homepage. Nondiscrimination policy: Creighton University is committed to providing a safe and non-discriminatory educational and employment environment. The University admits qualified students, hires qualified employees and accepts patients for treatment without regard to race, color, religion, sex, marital status, national origin, age, disability, citizenship, sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression, veteran status, or other status protected by law. Its education and employment policies, scholarship and loan programs, and other programs and activities, are administered without unlawful discrimination.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Schedule J, Part I, Line 1a First-class or charter travel
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The University paid for charter travel for two officers, a director, a key employee, and one of our highest compensated employees. In all cases, the charter travel was for business purposes, and accordingly, the cost of the charter travel was not treated as taxable compensation. The University President is provided housing on campus, which is required of his position. Club membership dues are paid for listed employees and are included in box 5 W-2 wages with the one exception of the University President who is a Jesuit priest and thus has no taxable compensation since his annual salary is paid directly to the religious order in accordance with his vow of poverty.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Schedule J, Part I, Line 1b Written policy regarding payment or reimbursement of expenses
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: As stated related to line 1a, the University President is the only listed person on Part VII, Section A, provided a residence. Therefore, there is no specific policy. The Club dues that are provided are specific to the related employee's employment contract instead of an overall policy with the one exception of the University President whose expenses are approved for the year by the Board of Trustees.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 11b Review of form 990 by governing body
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Form 990 is prepared and reviewed internally by management. Upon completion, the return is reviewed externally by an independent accounting firm. Then, the Risk Management, Audit and Compliance Committee of the Board of Trustees reviews the Form 990. Prior to filing, all members of the Board of Trustees are provided access to the Form 990 via e-mail communication.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 12c Conflict of interest policy
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: All University Senior Administrators and members of the Board of Trustees are required annually to submit a statement disclosing any potential conflicts of interest to the General Counsel/Board Secretary. Any potential conflicts disclosed by Senior Administrators are reviewed by the Risk Management, Audit and Compliance Subcommittee. Any potential conflicts disclosed by members of the Board of Trustees are reviewed by the Board's Executive Committee. These committees determine if further action is necessary to prevent or mitigate the conflict of interest.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 15a Process to establish compensation of top management official
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Review of the total compensation of the officers, key employees, and five highest-compensated other employees is conducted annually. The process involves collection of the market comparison data and individual performance evaluation ratings which are reviewed and considered by executive management in setting compensation for the coming year, followed by a review of the compensation and performance information by the President with the Board of Trustees Chair. The process is documented upon completion.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 19 Required documents available to the public
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The University conflict of interest policies and financial statements are located on the University website and are also available upon request.
